\section{Diversity}

The problem is that Weyl doesn't even attempt to retain the functionality of private property. Weyl writes that private property is not OPTED into in the first place, as such it seems justified to move to another system as well. But this misses that private property is the only knon system which, even if not opted into, allows agents to OPT out of further forceful imposition. Indeed private property allows communities to be independent of political and social trends. 


A grand confusion about the function of private property is the diversity it enables. Once a community figures out how to NOT depend on things outside of its domain, it allows communities to develop their own norms and evolve in their own independent paths. 

The problem of the economist is the readiness with which he imposes the profit constraint. While we can understand the importance of the profit constraint in the context of evolutionary forces of profit and loss, this is in fact, an intermediate stage. Indeed when one has not found a sustainable lifestyle, firms profits represent the enabling of other agents to search for their ends. But the goal of most people is not to always be subject to the market forces, indeed, many people only have to be slaves to the market process until they can figure out how to survive independly of the market process. 

The market process is the imposition of the measure by which one can gain independence. That measure, is money, or prices. 

Private property is the domain where agents can choose which measure to apply. For instance, one may judge the measure to be, how much plant surface it has, or may be the amount of ritualistic dance or a complex interaction of the two. This measure can create its own sub-competition. For instance, hunting tribe might decide that the mode of competition is how much elk is hunted, or an Amish community may decide that the measure of competition is productivity of crops, one may even decide that the measure of competition is the love displayed towards others. 

The natural measure of competition is violence. Indeed, this is often what democracy is about. 

Of course a property right is more than the selection of measure. It is also the right NOT to optimize. 



If two people have different values, that is, they have a specific structure/function that they want to maintain for a property. To maintain this structure they must either minimize their interaction with other functions or structures OR make their individual structure less costly. 

In fact you also choose your own measure about how to judge whether the property is going well or not. 

