\section{Salvage}

Can the same scheme be used by firms? The limitation of the scheme is that it does not discriminate between land with high allocational value and low investment value and land with high investment value and low allocational value. 

However presumably if a firm decides that a piece of land has high allocational value but low investment value and it values its own capacity to allocate to be less costly than the other firm, then this firm can bid more for it than other firms. Once the firm owns all the lands with high allocational value and low investment value

A second thing that I find salvageable is that the distinction between allocational and investment efficiency does not really exist in the intellectual property domain or at least does not really exist in the sense required. 

Suppose a firm has the intellectual asset of star wars. What does it mean for an author to be the allocational optimal? Well it means that this person can make the most from his labor. So while for instance another writer working on star wars can create a product worth 80 dollars(with the estate tax included). The optimal author can make a product worth 100. 

Now there are two avenues to advance here. 

First, what does it mean for the author to be the optimal allocation? Is the distinction between investment and allocational efficiency really something worthwhile? Well lets see, if he is the person who will make the most money off of it, what does it mean? If it means he will make the movie that will be the most successful then it is clear. What about investment efficiency? What does it mean for the system to be investment efficient? What does it mean to invest in the property in the intellectual context? Maybe it is to develop the world? Is there somebody who is developing the world he is creating without also being the allocationally optimal person? For instance George Rr Martin, may be, (debateably) the best person to improve the intellectual property, however what does this even mean? Does it mean that the property is increasing in value? How can it increase in value independently of the sales? Clearly if he develops the story but nobody reads it, then the value of the property has not increased. Indeed the property actually only increases in value according to sales, this means that allocational efficiency and investment efficiency are in fact interchangeable in the intellectual property domain. 

Second, it should be noted that we assume that the increase in capital efficiency is not important. What does this mean? Well suppose that there are two ways of using the property, a capital intensive way and a non-capital intensive way. If the capital is attached to the property, that is if the property is allocated to someone else WITH the property, then the allocated individual will be indifferent between the two methods, even if the capital intensive method actually gets a much higher output. 
Suppose that the capital is NOT part of the land but that it is also up for auction. What does this mean now? Well I would only bid for it according to how much it will augment my labor productivity on the land. However if it only augments my labor absolutely but it increases the labor productivity of EVERYONE in the same way, then I cannot be allocated the good, there has to be a DOUBLE coincidence for me to actually use this capital on the land, I have to both be the highest bidder on both. So the incentive to actually make this capital is the difference between MY capital augmentation and the SECOND persons capital augmentation. 

What if people can keep their capital as private property? Well here we have the incentive to invest that is at least the labor enhancing portion of the capital. Why? Suppose that this capital will also be land enhancing, then clearly this person will ALSO be able to extract the capital share from the land. In other words even if someone is unproductive in terms of labor, they may be the most productive from the capital point of view. 


